segments.text: The project houses, yes.
They were on the south side of the campus and they were large buildings and usually, I don't know how many youngsters, probably 10 or 12.
And usually it was a county operation and sometimes a widow parent would come, a mother usually, a woman.
and do the cooking and the kids brought canned stuff from home and so forth and so on.
They all seemed to have done well.
The ones I knew personally, of course my roommate was from blackest land and whitest people, Greenville.
Greenville.
And had a close friend over there we used to visit.
But I never did see, you know, it was,
It was like a military barracks in a sense.
You had all these guys, and I don't know how they figured out where to study or what.
And would, quite often, would they live there four years?
This depends.
Because some of them, a lot of them had part-time jobs cleaning up the dorms.
And later on, I guess they could move into the military units if they wanted to, and that would be part...
I was looking.
I think my dad, I was an out-of-state student for the first semester, and I think our tuition was $50.
The state, I think, was $25.
All right.
Basic division, and then what was your next assignment?
Well, I worked with Coach Bryant when he first came with academics,
And Jerry Claverin was their coach.
Scholastic person.
All right, tell me as much as you can about... Claverin.
Bryant and the whole... Oh, listen, he was an impressive guy.
I guess you go through life, and of course having been in the military, you see what I consider good leadership.
And I remember Willie Zappalack brought him over there
and introduced him to me.
And I looked at Coach Bryant, and he looked at me, and I had the feeling that he could see what I was saying, thinking, you know, like my dad could.
Boy, he could read me better than anybody I ever saw.
And he said, I'm glad to meet you.
And 20 years later, I went to a reunion, opened the back door, and
Coach Bryant said, hi, bud.
He said, I never did thank you for all the help you gave me.
I wasn't paid or anything.
Football ticket.
Then later on, when he left and Coach Myers was hired, they wanted me to go part-time, which I did.
With Coach Bryant, you did what?
You advised athletes?
Advised them.
checked on their grades, and we set up, I did with Bob Smith, set up a good computer type system that teachers could just fill out a card.
You may have seen that later on, and you just dropped it in the canvas.
Can you imagine what it'd be like today?
Was that the first time that had been done?
Oh yeah.
In fact, as I visited over at Coach Rawls, he was another one that was just
He said, y'all do more for the regular students over there than we do for athletes.
And Lance Hewlett had been over there a couple or three years.
And, you know, basic region had a lot.
It was ahead of its time.
Probably, well, they've got it running now in a different terminology, I guess.
All right.
Well, we want to come back to Bryant.
Let's go back.
Who started the basic division?
Who deserves the credit?

I often would have to tell you because I was working in the Veterans Administration for the education in psychology, and they kind of put this thing together as best I could understand, and then later on they said, well, we're going to close down the Veterans Testing Service because the deal had run out with the college.
It is after the war, though, the basic division.
Yeah, 50 or 51.
Okay.
Alright, back to Bryant.
Describe Bryant physically.
Big man.
Six feet?
Well, I couldn't tell you that really.
I only talked to him a couple of times in his four years here.
But I was really impressed with the caliber of kids that he had recruited.
He had a bum or two.
He doesn't ever get credit for the academics.
Because Charlie Krueger, I had cut him down to 12 hours, and he made 24 great ones, which is... Then, of course, he was... Now, listen, he went to high school in Caldwell.
Mm-hmm.
And was going up to Tarleton, and they hired Willie Zappalat to come here, and Charlie comes here.
Okay.
Now, Bryant's first year, he had recruited a ton of freshmen.
because there was no limit.
Yeah, I've got that list.
All right, in general, academically, those... Well, outside of one or two were good students.
Dennis Gehring, of course, had been out at Junction with me that previous year.
So I knew him.
I knew his parents, too.
He was from San Marcos.
And then they had, let's see,
the guy that started Church's Chicken.
When you see these guys 20 years later, it verifies what you thought at the time.
And I was in Foulboy.
Two that were already here one year when he came, that played in, Gene Stallings and Drake Keith.
Did you ever work with either of them?
Oh, yeah.
Well, they were good students.
Their main sweat was just making...
coaches cutting the roster.
I remember Gene talking about that.
Of course, I've got a fondness for him, I always have.
He was awfully young when he came here.
Alright, Coach Claiborne, Jerry Claiborne, what were his duties?
Well, he was basically, I don't know what area, they didn't have as many coaches in those days, but
I would imagine Bax or someone.
They lived over in Walton Hall, he and his wife.
But wasn't he the key person on the academic part?
He was the academic.
I mean, that was, I gave all the information to him and he'd come by.
You know, we had a good relationship and corresponded for years.
Conducted in tech and all over and stopped by to see him one time up there when he was out of his office.
Did, in the, do you recall any academic?
Five beta kappa.
I know he was, in history if I'm not mistaken.
Yes, and he had, Coach Bryant used to give a suit of clothes to the highest academic person on the ball court.
He wanted four years to grow.
Coach said, I'm going to quit giving this money.
Of course, you can't.
I guess that was legitimate in those days, as long as you didn't know about it.
I guess today you couldn't do that, could you?
Oh, this is like the federal government.
They got their hands all over you.
All right.
Any other academic prizes that you remember?
Oh, I remember D. Powell.
And let's see, the, I'm trying to think of the, Cawthorn, was he?
I almost have to go to a list.
All right.
Can you share any near misses where somebody just barely got by?
Not until later.
Okay.
All right.
So Coach Bryant is here four years.
Four years.
And you're the volunteer during that time.
Right.
So you're helping athletics on top of your basic division job.
Right.
and later on after he left and this was maybe a year later I found out that he had wanted to hire me full-time and Bertrand wouldn't let him talk to me.
Right now basic division during the Bryant years was directed by John Bertrand and he came about when?
I couldn't tell you that because that was all
They put it over there in the Aggieland Inn.
And I was clear across campus at Bazell, kind of like Snook was when I was a freshman.
Where is it?
And Pearl Harbor, where is it?
Okay, then, did you stay in?
Basic Division.
Okay, right.
And then when Coach Myers came, and of course that was an interesting story too,
board had three statements.
You may have heard this story.
No, please share it.
They had Eddie Erdelatz, Red Sanders, and Jim Myers down here in the MSC at the same time.
Alright, so that's the head coach at the Naval Academy at UCLA and Myers was Iowa State.
And that was the
deal when the kids sent that telegram that had all the signatures to Coach Meyer.
They hired him.
What kid?
The C. The CORE.
The CORE here.
Yeah.
As far as you're aware, who were the chief decision makers?
Couldn't tell you.
Was it the board?
Well, I guess.
I was there in the MSC and saw every one of them.
I mean, that's I. I take a note on that.
I don't know.
I can't even remember who was on the board because, you know, that's like general so-and-so.
Describe Coach Meyer's style.
Well, I was personally fond of Meyer.
One, he had children, and I'm talking with,
talking with him.
He could tell you, you know, when the kids were born and changing diapers.
He never got, you know, like Gene did when he came out there and put that big old office in there for the time.
Now, let's see.
So, and Coach Myers comes in 1958.
It was his first full season.
And we signed, I was at Junkie.
They signed 114 freshmen.
Of course, as far as I know, I came back to campus, nobody had filled out applications.
It was kind of a...
But then they recommended me full-time, and I interviewed with the athletic council, O.D.
Butler.
And then you went full-time.
Well, I talked.
two courses in education.
It was four-fifths.
Okay, and describe your duties then.
Well, it was one of those nice things.
I'm glad I had all the experiences.
Well, Bud will take care of this.
You know, all the books, all the course assignments, checking on their academics.
We had an episode there.
I can't remember.
It might have been with Hank or Fulberg or
Coach Myers, the little nurses over at the hospital were giving out those little chits, you know, the authorized absence, little white deals that they take to claim.
That may have been before your time.
And they put out a list, you know, remember at the end of the week, and they put a lot of those athletes on there.
Got that shut down real good.
Wait, the list of?
The authorized absence list came out, you know, in a big old mimeograph, legal sign.
Mm-hmm.
So there was a lot of, and of course we had athletes scattered all over the campus.
Dormitories, I had the housing.
Your responsibilities were all sports.
All sports, all scholarship, but we didn't.
And of course football, numerically football would have been by far the largest in number.
What sports did we have in those days?
Track.
Track was pretty big.
Basketball was, you know, wasn't too big, not like it is today.
Swimming, golf, tennis.
You left corner wrong.
Baseball.
Chandler was, you know, he was real good about taking care of his kids.
Shelby was, you know.
All right, so as you go over there, the head coaches were... Charlie Thomas.
No, not yet.
Was he?
Yeah.
Ray Putnam messed with the...
Colonel Andy had already retired?
Oh, yeah.
Okay, Charlie Thomas.
Then baseball.
Chandler.
Tom Chandler.
Bo Bell, I wasn't connected when Bo was over there.
That was in the early 50s, 51, 2, and 3, and of course mine.
Then basketball had the... Floyd.
Yeah.
And then Shelby was the freshman coach.
Which of those coaches were most academically concerned?
Well, Shelby was when he was freshman coach.
Charlie, you know, I shouldn't say this, but you know Charlie as well as I do, he'd rather be fishing probably.
But you had to keep it, you know, Charlie, some guy would call him and tell him, we've got this high jumper, jump six, five, which was, you know, that wasn't even possible in those days.
And he'd check, he'd,
called down to check out a car and Chandler, I was sitting there and Chandler said, Charlie, don't you think you ought to call some of the coaches in this district and see?
Well, it was five.
But that was later, let's see, Edgar?
I don't know, that's when we got all those sprinters that never hit a lick.
They were really, they were excellent high school, but they were always hurt when they got here.
All right, and once you're over there full time.
Then the tutorial program, the evening thing, four nights a week.
All right, when did, was that, was that a new, did the tutorial program start?
When we moved into Henderson.
Describe that.
Well, we had, I employed tutors.
And we were paying the outrageous salary of $1.50.
An hour?
An hour.
And I had some of the best.
Of course, they tend to group together.
They recommend a kid to you.
He's first class.
I mean, there was never any question.
You're saying tutors recommended new tutors?
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
And we had English, mathematics, and the sciences, both biology and chemistry.
And it was posted online.
They knew what nights the tutors would be there, and I'd go through Henderson and get them down there.
Of course, we'd have a few that were over playing pool, but Coach Myers kind of put it down.
Miss Murphy was the house mother, and the coaches were pretty tough on them.
Describe dormitory life in Henderson Hall.
I'll tell you one thing that I did, and you know, you look back on these things and it's kind of funny today, but I had two areas that I insisted that every student take with electing.
One was business law, both courses, and the other one was old Bob Boone's music appreciation.
Now when those kids come in at the beginning of the year, you could walk down the hall

You talk about the conglomerate of music, or lack of music, as I used to joke, and then as they move on down to junior year after they've had Boone's course, and I told Bob this, I said, it just did your heart good to see that after all we were putting some class on, but they just never had been exposed to it.
Well, as you recall, what was their favorite major?
Engineering.
That certainly wasn't an easy one.
It wasn't a pushover.
Of course we had the two Hargit's for instance.
They were just outstanding.
I had one of them that played quarterback in my class.
I remember what grade he made for me.
He came in the dorm one night and just looked like
Death warmed over and I said, what's the matter?
And he said, I made 46 on that physics test.
And I said, what was the highest grade?
I said, what are you worried about?
And they were, boy, they were mean in that basic physics and engineering class.
I often wondered if it wouldn't be better to let them take it later.
And I did.
On a lot of students, I wouldn't let them take chemistry 101 until the second semester.
You're in a smaller class, you've got your better teachers.
That's how I worked anyway.
What was kind of the major of last resort?
If they couldn't make it in anything else, where did they go?
I don't really remember, because I didn't have
We really didn't have that many students.
I think one time I figured out we had, Myers was shocked.
I compiled some statistics sometime in his second or third year.
Hell, 85% of the kids were graduating.
The football.
Of course, we weren't winning any football.
Of course, he knew that later.
Which sports had the highest graduation rate, you think?
Surprisingly, golf.
Okay, I'm not surprised.
And Henry Ransom was about as loose jointed as any coach I've ever met.
He called me the night before and said, will you want to take the boys up to Arkansas?
I said, not on short notice, Henry.
Don't do this.
What about some of the stunts or pranks that you remember that they did in or around Henderson Hall?
Well, I just, they were pretty good because I was over there usually from 7 till 9 or 9.30, just depending on what was going on.
I just never had any difficulty.
I was trying to think of this little old guard, had his car parked out in that little area back of the chapel.
It was a little kind of a driveway looking thing.
He went out one morning and his engine had been fanned out tonight.
I wish I could think of anything.
He was from San Antonio.
This was done by some of his buddies?
No, I think somebody else.
Oh, really?
We used to have trouble until Meeks and I got the school to come in and put iron bars.
They'd come through the steam tunnels and come in down in the electrical stuff down in our
deal.
That was really dangerous.
You mentioned Meeks.
Tell me about that man.
He was a classic.
Of course, I was especially fond of him because his wife talked to my boys.
And his, what's his full name?
I don't know.
S.M.
was all I knew.
And you all called him Monk.
And his duties were?
Everything like mine is equipment, basically.
But he was kind of a father confessor.
He and old Pickard both.
And he came over here about what, when?
Came with bones, so I guess that would be late.
Late 50s.
Oh, yeah.
Because I came, in the summer of 59, I taught at Shriner in Kerrville before coming over here.
And I came over with his son.
His older boy was there.
SM Junior was there.
coach there and came over and spent the night in Henderson Hall looking for an apartment.
So where did you find the apartment?
Well, we found a house out on Cindy Lane across from Lynn the Shoe Factory for $85 a month, which we thought was really high priced because I made $5.50 a month for nine months.
That was my job.
Well, you know, that was interesting.
We were talking about that on that college station thing.
When I finished school, I went over to Groveton to interview a friend of mine who was head coach.
Three classes of history, three sports.
And that was $2,400.
And they offered me this director of the counseling center, $3,600.
For 12 months, man.
$300 a month.
And I thought, boy, that
That was something.
All right, these other staff members in athletics, who was the head trainer in the 50s?
Billy, I guess.
Who?
Billy Pickard.
Billy Pickard?
Yeah.
Before, now, Hank brought in a guy.
I'm trying to think.
There's a policeman, or used to be the spokesman for the Bryan Police Department.
He lived out on Luzia Lane.
But he left here and went to Tulane.
He was a good trainer.
And who was the business officer?
Pat Dyle.
Describe.
Well, Pat was, he was an unusual guy.
I was really overwhelmed at the tremendous job that he did with tickets.
I didn't, you know, not having been exposed to that until I went to work full time and you go down there
See this little one, so much bigger than this.
All the tickets for all the sports and the season passes.
It wasn't that big an operation.
Now, who was the athletic director?
Well, Myers, I guess.
I'm not sure if Myers was the athletic director.
I think Bones was brought in by Brian.
Now, you haven't given him his full name yet.
Who?
Barlow.
Barlow.
Barlow, Bones, Earl.
You know, it goes through all this line.
He came from San Antonio, I believe, didn't he?
Yeah, I think Brian must have hired him.
I guess that's about it.
Small, I can remember the day close to just before leaving when we had a million dollar budget.
Bones, that was a shock.
As far as you know, knew then, was the budget balanced at Athletics Page?
Oh yeah, they were in the black.
That's one thing Bones could do.
And, you know, for me to go and say, now this Tiff has been here a year, I think he needs at least a quarter more raise.
Now, let me think about it.
Well, I knew I had Bones.
Bones knew
We were doing a good job in the academic area, and I never had any problem with that.
Alright, on the athletic part, as you now look back on it, what were the things that y'all were doing that obviously...
Guidance, real.
We took a guidance program that had been through the Veterans Administration, through the basic division, through the adjunct program,
and took the best parts of all of that.
And it's the contact with the student.
They know you're there.
They can depend on you.
And I always felt they had a feeling that I wasn't gonna mess them up.
And I had two or three athletes like old Ken Tim and some of the basketball, old dude, Doug McClain is McClain's coach.
Yeah.
He was the best-read student we had in the dormitory.
Did you ever know that?
He read all the time.
Now, I don't know if he didn't kill himself on his textbooks, probably.
But he came up to me one time.
I insisted the juniors go to the Registrar's office and check their credits.
I had a running thing in the office.
tried to apprise him, particularly guys like dude, but he doesn't pay attention.
So he comes up his last, his senior semester.
Am I going to graduate?
And I said, now, dude, did you go there?
No.
Did you go this year?
No.
I said, well, you lack about 15, 16 more credits.
No, I guess it was 24 to
to graduate.
Well, he stayed over at Stallings, you remember, and did a good job.
Went to law school.
Let me tell you my favorite one.
He took my Old South Advanced History course, and you had to do a term paper.
And when I got to his term paper, Harry, what's his name?
No, go ahead.
This dude, McLean.
Oh, yeah.
Dude.
And he turned in a term paper, and I started reading it.
And each paragraph began with quotation marks and ended with quotation marks.
There was not a single grammatical error.
Everything, every paragraph had a footnote.
But none of the paragraph, and there was a long bibliography, and all, everything, but
None of the paragraphs had any particular relationship to any of the other paragraphs.
And so I put an F on it, passed it out, and with a note, come see me.
He came in and I said, dude, explain this to me.
He said, well, as you can probably see, that's not my work.
And I said, oh.
He said, I put it off until the last minute.
And I then went to the library and checked out about two dozen books.
And I just put marks on various pages and told the secretary to type those up and take the first paragraph on each page.
And I thought maybe that you would be in a hurry and you'd just glance at it and give me a grade.
And I said, well, you know, I've got to give you an F. And he said, I'm not surprised at all.
And he grinned and went on.
And we both chuckled about it.
I told him, I said, dude, I'll probably tell this story a good many times.
He did the same thing to Charlie McCandless.
Is that right?
No, no.
As you know, Dr. McCandless.
This was Charles Gaddon's course, 426.
Charles McCandless.
Charles McCandless.
And I go over there, and he hands me this thing, and I look at the bibliography.
It was a paper just like that.
I looked at the bibliography, and looked at the front, the table, contents, and everything.
And then I got to thumbing through it, and I said, I wonder where he got it.
It was my paper.
I don't know where.
Maybe...
I'm sure it wasn't in the old boys' file because we didn't keep stuff like that.
You mentioned Hargetts.
Who are some others you look back on with great pride as being proud to have worked with them?
You get in Jeff Andrick, the insurance guy here.
Lloyd Curry.
I mean, guys, well, Currington had to work hard.
There was a kid from Kern, Franklin.
I really can't.
Ellison, I gave him a Bible for graduation because he was big.
Carter?
Carter Franklin.
His highest test score on any of his tests at admission was a 4%.
He was an honor.
He won the graduate fellowship that they gave.
At the same time, I said, what did you do with, he got a set of encyclopedias, gave them to his daughter, I mean to his sister who was at Baylor, one of the junior colleges.
We correspond spasmodically now, but those guys are in their 60s.
But old dude, he was one that he and Ken Timmons, I finally talked to him.
